164
00:20:38,940 --> 00:20:47,360
 I mean, I, I get kind of anxious when I talk, you know, sometimes I don't know what I'm going to say or if I'm going to say something the right way, if I'm going to stutter on my words.

165
00:20:48,200 --> 00:21:01,120
 But I learned that, you know, when, especially when I entered religious life, one of the biggest things for me when I entered religious life was like a fear of speaking.

166
00:21:02,220 --> 00:21:14,620
 That I'm not going to be able to talk in front of people because, and this goes all the way back to like that rejection of in woodshop, that experience of being told I was stupid.

167
00:21:14,620 --> 00:21:15,480
 Right.

168
00:21:16,060 --> 00:21:23,660
 So like I had to get over that, like I had to like, in a sense, reach through that and keep persevering through that.

169
00:21:23,660 --> 00:21:36,660
 And so through the years of, um, being in seminary and then being a friar, being on EWTN, I mean, I never thought in a million years that I'd have a microphone in front of me.

170
00:21:36,900 --> 00:21:57,540
 And that I'd be talking, you know, with, with people be talking, you know, you know, I, I like to think that, I mean, like when we preach, when we preach and teach the gospel, when we're giving a homily, I know what, I know what I like when I, when I listen to a homily, I don't like to be talked at.

171
00:21:57,540 --> 00:22:05,860
 I don't like to be preached at like, to be like, I actually, I think it's more effective when you're like, like a homily is supposed to be like a dialogue.

172
00:22:06,180 --> 00:22:10,100
 Like the way, like Fulton Sheen, the preach, I think he's a great example.

173
00:22:10,100 --> 00:22:17,780
 I tried to learn from him and the way that he preached and, and taught is the way that he would pause and the way that he would speak.

174
00:22:17,780 --> 00:22:31,460
 He would give people time to like, think like the pause and not just be like, I, there's some people that just like preach and they preach a million miles an hour at you.

175
00:22:31,460 --> 00:22:35,500
 And after 10 minutes, I, I don't know what the, they said.

176
00:22:35,500 --> 00:22:38,540
 I don't, I have no idea what they said and I don't care.

177
00:22:38,540 --> 00:22:45,480
 You know, I like, like, like I want to be like, I want to be in relationship with people.

178
00:22:45,480 --> 00:22:46,040
 Yeah.

179
00:22:46,040 --> 00:22:53,680
 And I think that like, I think the most effective communicators are people that like bring you into relationship.

180
00:22:53,680 --> 00:22:58,740
 I think, I think, I think of people like, you know, one of my friends, Chris Stefanik.

181
00:22:58,740 --> 00:23:02,840
 Chris Stefanik is a, is a great communicator.

182
00:23:02,840 --> 00:23:10,720
 The way that he, he gets across to people through the media, through podcasts, like he draws people in through like relationship.

183
00:23:11,280 --> 00:23:25,040
 You know, he looks into the camera, you know, I think, you know, mother Angelica had, had that, that gift that when she looked into the camera, she said, family, we're going to talk about Jesus tonight.

184
00:23:26,720 --> 00:23:29,520
 And she would talk about real things.

185
00:23:29,520 --> 00:23:30,740
 She would talk about suffering.

186
00:23:30,740 --> 00:23:35,780
 Mother talked about her own, you know, sufferings in life, her own failures even.

187
00:23:36,020 --> 00:23:39,900
 And why do you think people actually liked her and identified with her?

188
00:23:39,900 --> 00:23:42,020
 Because like, they saw themselves.

189
00:23:42,020 --> 00:23:44,140
 They're like, this lady's real.

190
00:23:44,140 --> 00:23:46,640
 Like, she's not putting on a fake show.

191
00:23:46,640 --> 00:23:48,340
 Like, she's real.

192
00:23:48,340 --> 00:23:52,780
 And like, like, if she can be a Christian, then, then I think I can.

193
00:23:52,780 --> 00:23:56,780
 Like, I think I can overcome my failures if this lady has.

194
00:23:57,180 --> 00:24:07,960
 And father, what do you think mother Angelica would think of, of kind of this day and age, this kind of AI powered age also where, you know, people are talking about AI film studios.

195
00:24:07,960 --> 00:24:09,480
 They're talking about AI books.

196
00:24:09,480 --> 00:24:13,900
 They're talking about AI, you know, pastors and priests and sermons.

197
00:24:13,900 --> 00:24:16,680
 I think she'd be very worried, actually.

198
00:24:16,680 --> 00:24:20,000
 I don't think mother Angelica is afraid of technology.

199
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:22,040
 I think we know that.

200
00:24:22,520 --> 00:24:33,340
 I mean, there's all kinds of technology that we use at EWTN through the years, innovative stuff that, you know, Mother Angelica was like a pioneer of, right?

201
00:24:33,340 --> 00:24:43,020
 But I think that she would always go back to silence, spending time in silence before the Blessed Sacrament.

202
00:24:43,020 --> 00:24:43,940
 Why?

203
00:24:45,900 --> 00:24:53,600
 I think that she had so much to say in front of things like this, in front of a microphone, in front of the TV.

204
00:24:53,600 --> 00:24:59,480
 I think she had so much to say because she spent so much time in recollection.

205
00:24:59,480 --> 00:25:09,160
 It wasn't just because that she was, you know, educated and went to a pontifical university.

206
00:25:09,160 --> 00:25:11,120
 And, you know, she didn't do any of those things.

207
00:25:12,300 --> 00:25:23,500
 I think that she really, like, knew what to say and knew how to talk to people based on her relationship with Jesus.

208
00:25:23,500 --> 00:25:33,640
 Bar, like, first and foremost, bar none, like, her relationship with Christ, her experience of being loved by God.

209
00:25:34,640 --> 00:25:47,740
 I think when it comes back to it, everything in her life that she spoke about on television, that she communicated, all came back to her relationship, her relationship with Jesus.

210
00:25:49,080 --> 00:25:57,080
 And I think that's what we can teach people as priests, as lay people, you know, doing communication.

211
00:25:57,080 --> 00:26:06,080
 We can teach people to pause, to take time in their life to pray, to be silent.

212
00:26:06,720 --> 00:26:16,900
 I think Pope Leo actually talked about that recently in, when you talk a lot about education, the importance of contemplation, the importance of silence.

213
00:26:18,840 --> 00:26:28,400
 And these things are crucial in the Christian life, not to be completely immersed with noise, because I know what that's like.

214
00:26:28,400 --> 00:26:30,360
 And you do too, Ben.

215
00:26:30,360 --> 00:26:31,560
 And we've talked about this a lot.

216
00:26:31,560 --> 00:26:35,740
 It's like we, at the end of the day, we are tired.

217
00:26:35,740 --> 00:26:37,520
 We are, we are dead.

218
00:26:38,740 --> 00:26:46,760
 We don't even want to pray at the end of the day, because we've been bombarded by noise and, and screens and technology all day long.

219
00:26:46,760 --> 00:26:57,560
 I think when we maybe start the day in recollection, start the day in silence, have periods throughout the day in silence.

220
00:26:58,340 --> 00:27:04,320
 I often, as, as chaplain of EWTN, I'm, I'm the employee chaplain for EWTN.

221
00:27:04,320 --> 00:27:23,640
 So, uh, I try and encourage employees, uh, to pray throughout the day, to take time to pray, uh, because I see what a difference it makes in our productivity, in the way we write articles, in the way we handle ourselves with people.

222
00:27:24,300 --> 00:27:54,000
 Um, I, I think there's a lot to be said with just taking time to pray, um, to spend time in silence and Eucharistic adoration, not just going to mass, but I think prolonged periods of Eucharistic adoration and just start with five minutes a day, even five minutes a week, 10 minutes a week before the Eucharist, just sit there, just be silent and talk to them.

223
00:27:54,300 --> 00:28:01,320
 Tell him what's going on. He already knows. Um, but I, I think we need to, to recover that.

224
00:28:01,320 --> 00:28:09,060
 And father, um, you know, on, on a, on a practical level, where do you see AI potentially being a real tool, a real helper?

225
00:28:09,060 --> 00:28:27,500
 Well, um, for me, um, I'm a auditory learner, so I, I use it all the time, uh, in reading documents, uh, a document that would take me like literally days or weeks to get through because of comprehension.

226
00:28:27,860 --> 00:28:36,300
 Uh, I think when I read something from, uh, beginning to end, like going from paragraph to paragraph, I have a hard time focusing.

227
00:28:36,300 --> 00:28:48,200
 Um, so when I have something, um, when I read and hear it, uh, through an app called speechify, I use all the time.

228
00:28:48,700 --> 00:28:54,500
 Um, and I, even today I was using it, you know, to kind of go through a document.

229
00:28:54,500 --> 00:29:00,660
 I see the texts being, um, highlighted, you know, so I'm, I'm actually engaging my senses.

230
00:29:00,660 --> 00:29:13,040
 I'm, I'm looking at the text I'm reading and at the same time I'm hearing, uh, so I can get through a whole document within, you know, less than a couple hours.

231
00:29:13,040 --> 00:29:22,440
 That would normally take me probably a week to go through and I feel like I actually learn it better by doing it that way, by, by engaging the senses.

232
00:29:22,440 --> 00:29:25,580
 And that's all that's used through, that's AI technology.

233
00:29:25,580 --> 00:29:42,280
 Um, also, um, you know, sometimes we're busy in, in homily preparation and if we're preaching every day, uh, if we have like talks to do, um, you know, sometimes I think it's helpful to get like, um, a start.

234
00:29:43,040 --> 00:30:01,320
 Uh, in homily preparation, uh, maybe for the weekend or a couple of days out, you know, I might put in, um, just something, something like, um, I'm preaching a homily, uh, in a couple of days or tomorrow on these particular readings.

235
00:30:01,440 --> 00:30:11,220
 And I'll put in the readings, um, and then I'll also put, uh, just some questions like, uh, or I'll put, it's a, it's a saint day.

236
00:30:11,220 --> 00:30:12,800
 It's St. Maria Goretti's feast day.

237
00:30:12,800 --> 00:30:14,960
 It's St. Pope St. John Paul II's feast day.

238
00:30:14,960 --> 00:30:21,960
 Did John Paul II say anything about this gospel in his homilies, uh, during when he was Pope?

239
00:30:22,300 --> 00:30:27,440
 Did Pope Benedict say anything about this particular gospel of the good Samaritan?

240
00:30:27,440 --> 00:30:33,300
 Did St. Augustine say anything about this in relation to Catholic education?

241
00:30:33,300 --> 00:30:34,300
 Enter.

242
00:30:34,300 --> 00:30:35,780
 Bam.

243
00:30:35,780 --> 00:30:40,680
 And you have like this whole corpus of stuff to work with.

244
00:30:41,060 --> 00:30:44,300
 And so I can read through it and be like, oh, that's a great start.

245
00:30:44,300 --> 00:30:48,160
 I mean, this is, it's getting my mind ready in preparation for preaching.

246
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:52,500
 Um, and it just, it gives me crumbs to deal with.

247
00:30:52,500 --> 00:31:06,700
 It gives me stuff to pull from that I can use this, this, uh, um, you know, kind of information that AI gives you, uh, for, for good purposes to preach the gospel, to communicate with people.

248
00:31:07,420 --> 00:31:12,060
 Um, and you can always ask more questions too, as the time goes along.

249
00:31:12,060 --> 00:31:14,960
 Um, you can kind of build on that.

250
00:31:14,960 --> 00:31:19,680
 So I think we can use, we can use it responsibly.

251
00:31:19,680 --> 00:31:34,600
 I think we can, it's all in, it's all in our intention and how we use, uh, technology and we can use technology to be, you know, to, to take, uh, to take, take, take, you know, for ourselves.

252
00:31:35,200 --> 00:31:37,640
 And to be like greedy, right.

253
00:31:37,640 --> 00:31:45,800
 But I, I think, I think we, like, we need to be open-handed, you know, like, um, what, what's the Psalm open-handed?

254
00:31:45,800 --> 00:31:49,580
 He gives to the poor, his justice, his prosperity endures forever.

255
00:31:50,420 --> 00:32:01,940
 So if we live as like open-handed and like not wanting to clutch things, not wanting to even clutch or possess technology is like mine, mine, mine.

256
00:32:02,180 --> 00:32:18,580
 But like use as a good steward using technology and in a healthy way and wanting to, you know, first of all, be a better steward of creation, better and to handle on the faith, to handle on the faith that I've received.

257
00:32:18,820 --> 00:32:23,660
 I think that's a healthy way of looking at using technology properly.

258
00:32:23,660 --> 00:32:29,200
 That's not wanting to have it possess you because we can let technology possess us.

259
00:32:29,200 --> 00:32:39,380
 But I think in a healthy way, uh, is how, how are we using technology and not allowing it to possess us?

260
00:32:39,380 --> 00:32:44,280
 But do we possess it, you know, rather than have it possess us?

261
00:32:44,280 --> 00:32:57,100
 One thing that I've, I've seen, and this has been on kind of Catholic media, um, there's been, you know, public intellectuals who are, who are Christian, who've, who've talked about this is kind of, you know, the fear of the demonic inside of AI.

262
00:32:57,100 --> 00:33:13,300
 There's people, you know, kind of going through those gradients who, who very much feel that we're summoning the devil when we're talking about AIs that these, that these are, that these are, um, dark forces, um, that are also, you know, creating a system that, that is very scary.

263
00:33:13,300 --> 00:33:32,800
 Well, we want to be connected to, again, going back to the primary relationships, you know, that, you know, um, that we are in a state of grace, uh, that we are participation in the sacraments that we're receiving, uh, holy communion, uh, often in the state of grace.

264
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:42,440
 And that, uh, we go to confession often, uh, receiving the sacrament of, of Christ's mercy and, and just living in God.

265
00:33:42,640 --> 00:33:50,960
 That, that, that's going to help the way that we navigate technology too, because we're not going to be seeking out false reality.

266
00:33:50,960 --> 00:33:56,540
 We're not going to be seeking out, um, uh, sinful behaviors.

267
00:33:56,540 --> 00:34:02,380
 And basically, I mean, uh, you know, quite frankly, I think we're not going to be opening up doors.

268
00:34:02,380 --> 00:34:10,060
 C.S. Lewis says that hell is everybody's back turned away from one another.

269
00:34:10,480 --> 00:34:15,260
 And I think all of us can say, yeah, I've experienced that.

270
00:34:15,260 --> 00:34:27,600
 Like I've experienced like some hell in my life, some being turned away from people, like, like, like cut off from people, desolation from people, like separation from people, even separation from God.

271
00:34:27,600 --> 00:34:41,660
 You know, um, but heaven is actually relationship communion, actually speaking like loving, fully loving, fully engaged in another person's life.

272
00:34:41,920 --> 00:34:43,560
 That's what heaven's going to be like.

273
00:34:43,560 --> 00:34:45,520
 So we can, we can live heaven now.

274
00:34:46,820 --> 00:34:48,600
 Or we can leave hell now.

275
00:34:48,600 --> 00:34:51,800
 You know, I think that's, that's our choice.

276
00:34:51,800 --> 00:34:57,140
 Um, now can technology help us to be better communicators?

277
00:34:57,140 --> 00:34:59,240
 Um, sure.

278
00:34:59,680 --> 00:35:03,220
 You can follow in the footsteps of Carlo Acutis, who was recently a candidate.

279
00:35:03,220 --> 00:35:03,500
 It can help us.

280
00:35:03,500 --> 00:35:04,500
 Absolutely.

281
00:35:04,500 --> 00:35:06,860
 It can help us to do, to do great things.

282
00:35:06,860 --> 00:35:08,980
 Like he wanted to bring people to the Eucharist.

283
00:35:08,980 --> 00:35:14,660
 Like, so, so he developed, he put, he put Eucharistic miracles online.

284
00:35:14,960 --> 00:35:28,200
 And how many people have benefited from his putting together on the computer, a database of all the Eucharistic miracles in the world.

285
00:35:28,200 --> 00:35:39,300
 How many people have come to know Jesus in the real presence and come to full communion with the church because of this 15 year old boy who died, you know, of leukemia.

286
00:35:39,300 --> 00:35:41,200
 He's now canonized a lot.

287
00:35:41,980 --> 00:35:46,080
 You know, so we can use technology for incredible things.

288
00:35:46,080 --> 00:35:59,540
 And I'm sure people will come up with, with even more creative ways to, you know, to use, um, you know, technology and, and to use it in a, in a, in a Christian way, in a moral way.

289
00:35:59,540 --> 00:36:01,720
 Intentionality is important.

290
00:36:01,720 --> 00:36:08,060
 How do we, how do we sit down and use this equipment that has been entrusted to us?

291
00:36:08,060 --> 00:36:11,960
 Um, you know, cause we can use it to tear down.

292
00:36:11,980 --> 00:36:23,020
 We can use it to tear down society or we can use it to build up the body of Christ and to help contribute to the healing of the world, the salvation of the world.

293
00:36:23,020 --> 00:36:23,880
 I love that.

294
00:36:23,880 --> 00:36:26,700
 Father, maybe one last question while I have you here.

295
00:36:27,700 --> 00:36:35,060
 I feel that, you know, this, these years, these times, there's a lot of, there's a lot of tension, a lot of fear, a lot of, um, kind of negativity around the future.

296
00:36:35,620 --> 00:36:44,300
 And, um, you know, as, as a, as a, as a, as a man of God, as a, as a, as a father, can I ask, um, as we end, like what gives you hope?

297
00:36:44,300 --> 00:36:45,580
 What keeps you optimistic?

298
00:36:45,580 --> 00:36:48,280
 The best thing I do is to hear confessions.

299
00:36:48,280 --> 00:36:52,960
 The holiness of the church is manifested in the confessional.

300
00:36:52,960 --> 00:36:55,460
 That's where you see how good people really are.

301
00:36:55,460 --> 00:37:07,320
 Um, it's, it's, it's not the, the sins that people confess, um, the weaknesses, the failures that people confess, um, uh, that it doesn't get me down.

302
00:37:07,320 --> 00:37:15,360
 It doesn't, you know, somehow crush me and think, oh gosh, you know, uh, again, you know, I'm hearing this again and again and again.

303
00:37:15,360 --> 00:37:27,600
 Um, no, actually the confessional is a place where, uh, we as sinners, as penitents come into contact with the mercy of God.

304
00:37:29,280 --> 00:37:41,980
 And it is a miracle for anybody to humble themselves, to get down on their knees and to confess into another person's ear.

305
00:37:41,980 --> 00:37:50,480
 The most shameful things that they've done in their life, you know, people that have been away from the faith for decades.

306
00:37:50,480 --> 00:37:56,500
 Um, you know, I always tell people all the time, think about, um,

307
00:37:57,740 --> 00:38:07,460
 If you've only had five hours left on this earth before you meet God, um, and that's that you're going to meet God face to face.

308
00:38:07,460 --> 00:38:10,220
 Like, what is it in your life that you were holding on to?

309
00:38:10,220 --> 00:38:26,280
 Uh, if there's anything in your life that you haven't confessed or has forgiveness for, what is it in your life that, um, that you need to ask God forgiveness for, for healing for, and let it go.

310
00:38:26,700 --> 00:38:28,420
 You say it out loud.

311
00:38:28,420 --> 00:38:34,580
 Christ wants you to let it go and to, to seek forgiveness, to seek reconciliation, to seek healing.

312
00:38:34,580 --> 00:38:38,540
 Um, and that happens in the sacrament of penance.

313
00:38:38,540 --> 00:38:43,740
 You know, I think people, um, probably do that on, through chatbots.

314
00:38:43,740 --> 00:38:49,240
 You know, they probably talk about their failures and they probably receive advice from,

315
00:38:49,420 --> 00:38:52,060
 from AI, from chatbots and stuff.

316
00:38:52,060 --> 00:39:02,380
 And they receive, you know, things back, but in confession, you know, you're coming before the throne of grace.

317
00:39:03,480 --> 00:39:06,100
 Um, and there's something, there's a wisdom.

318
00:39:06,100 --> 00:39:09,160
 I mean, Christ is the one who instituted the sacrament of penance.

319
00:39:09,160 --> 00:39:16,120
 I always like to say, say to people say that, um, Jesus Christ is the best psychologist that ever existed.

320
00:39:16,920 --> 00:39:20,480
 He's God, he's a God man, but he knows human psychology.

321
00:39:20,480 --> 00:39:24,280
 He knows that we need to hear in our ear.

322
00:39:24,280 --> 00:39:29,460
 We need to hear that we've been forgiven, that we've been absolved, you know?

323
00:39:29,460 --> 00:39:37,860
 And those, those words that I say, you know, when I was able to give, um, my dad, um, uh,

324
00:39:37,860 --> 00:39:44,060
 absolution, you know, the moment he died, you know, um, I, I looked down and put my stole on,

325
00:39:44,060 --> 00:39:49,220
 I had my oils, you know, and I said, you know, God, the father of mercies through the death

326
00:39:49,220 --> 00:39:53,560
 and resurrection of his son has reconciled the world to himself and poured out the Holy

327
00:39:53,560 --> 00:39:57,400
 spirit for the forgiveness of sins through the ministry of the church.

328
00:39:57,400 --> 00:39:59,380
 May God grant you pardon and peace.

329
00:39:59,380 --> 00:40:05,200
 And I absolve you from your sins in the name of the father and of a son and of a Holy spirit.

330
00:40:05,200 --> 00:40:05,560
 Amen.

331
00:40:05,560 --> 00:40:11,020
 And I dip my finger in the holy oil, anointed his forehead through this holy anointing.

332
00:40:11,020 --> 00:40:16,120
 May the Lord in his love and mercy help you with the grace of the Holy spirit anointed his hands.

333
00:40:16,120 --> 00:40:20,220
 May the Lord, he frees you from sin, save you and raise you up.

334
00:40:20,220 --> 00:40:25,920
 And I went straight into the apostolic pardon by the authority granted to me by the apostolic sea.

335
00:40:25,920 --> 00:40:32,260
 I grant you a full pardon and remission of all your sins in the name of the father and of the son and the Holy spirit.

336
00:40:32,260 --> 00:40:32,700
 Amen.

337
00:40:32,700 --> 00:40:34,720
 And my dad died.

338
00:40:34,720 --> 00:40:39,300
 At that moment, like he died.

339
00:40:40,060 --> 00:40:43,620
 As I was giving him last night as the apostolic pardon.

340
00:40:43,620 --> 00:40:55,960
 And so that, that he would close his eyes to this world and that he would open his eyes to see the, he would see the face of Jesus, you know, only God can arrange something like that.

341
00:40:56,620 --> 00:41:18,020
 You know, so like, like the brokenness, like, like even in my own relationship with my father, having some brokenness in that, in that relationship, uh, because of my parents' divorce and separation, you know, having my dad going back to what my, my dad saying to me about, you know, that he was going to take his life and how he was going to do it.

342
00:41:18,080 --> 00:41:23,120
 That's where anxiety enters into my life was through my, my dad doing that.

343
00:41:23,120 --> 00:41:23,540
 Right.

344
00:41:24,420 --> 00:41:29,220
 But God allowing me at that moment to give my dad absolution.

345
00:41:29,220 --> 00:41:31,920
 That's God healing.

346
00:41:31,920 --> 00:41:34,200
 That's God healing through relationship.

347
00:41:34,200 --> 00:41:36,820
 So I am incredibly grateful.

348
00:41:36,820 --> 00:41:38,440
 That's beautiful.

349
00:41:38,440 --> 00:41:46,180
 And on that note, I think, um, this is a wonderful, uh, spot to end, um, Father John Paul, thank you so much, uh, for your time today.

350
00:41:46,180 --> 00:41:46,920
 You're welcome.

351
00:41:46,920 --> 00:41:53,280
 Um, and this is a reminder to all of you to go to confession, to speak to real people, to live in the real world.

352
00:41:53,880 --> 00:41:54,900
 Thank you so much, Father.

353
00:41:54,900 --> 00:41:55,640
 You're welcome.

354
00:41:55,640 --> 00:41:56,640
 It's good to be here, Ben.

